Lessons that can still be learned from the Cuban Missile Crisis
"Thirteen Days" („Dreizehn Tage“), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, is set to open in cinemas in numerous countries soon.
Everyone should watch this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events—particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a U.S. national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy convened his closest advisors at the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the establishment of a nuclear weapons installation on Cuba.
The decisions made during the following thirteen days and the decisions that could not be reached would have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened during these days at the White House.
Audio recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the premiere of the film in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard initiated a discussion session intended to examine the film and the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this session included: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a professor of history at Harvard who wrote a book on the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a professor of Political Science at Harvard, who presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision," thirty years ago.
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the film's treatment of the subject was criticized in various aspects, the discussion participants agreed that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressures with which President Kennedy was confronted, as they actually were.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Missile Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in the case of a crisis, but it is exclusively the President who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – civilian as well as military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be highlighted, which were essential in determining the consequences.
It is necessary to understand how an adversary thinks; in addition, the communication lines must remain open.
To corner an adversary without maintaining diplomatic channels that allow for an understanding of the adversary's situation could prove disastrous.
· The United States depends on allies.
Kennedy therefore acted in this way because NATO, other allies, and the opinion of the world had supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into taking action.
The fact that a week passed in which all involved factors were examined and weighed with the utmost precision was crucial to the outcome.
But would such a period of time for deliberation still exist today in light of the mass media that currently exist?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the adversary's position.
In one of the much-criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade, which Kennedy had imposed over Cuba, was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intent, and was not meant as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted more calmly?
After all, the United States had also stationed nuclear warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles on Cuba merely reflected this policy.
Yet Kennedy showed anxiety regarding the consequences that a stationing of Soviet missiles on Cuba would have had with respect to Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
In the end, "the Berlin Crisis was resolved through the outcomes of the Cuban Missile Crisis," as claimed by the historian Ernest May.
"Bald wird es zu spät sein," was a widely held argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba, even while the rockets – as they assumed – were en route to Cuba by sea.
A U.S. force of about 180,000 troops was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a lightning bombardment that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that there had already been nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those 90 were strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received these information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He posed Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about this?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro answered: "I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that nuclear weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba.
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were willing to let Cuba burn to ashes so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion could therefore have resulted in the deaths of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because Kennedy's government lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is firmly convinced that an invasion would certainly have led to a Soviet nuclear attack on the United States.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military on Cuba was indeed limited: airplanes of the U-2 type, which flew over Cuban airspace, were shot down despite the chairman's explicit instructions to the contrary.
A difficult question that did not arise during this debate at Harvard is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who during the crisis was more characterized by rational behavior, but rather someone of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the context and maintaining consistency with the established translation style and proper nouns, the English translation of the German sentence is:
The current discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in light of this terrible, yet entirely realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new Web site on the Internet, where the essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis as well as current nuclear threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
